y-first-century drama, this project examines performances of blackness’s deadpan aesthetic within and beyond black embodiments, including Young Jean Lee’s The Shipment and Branden Jacobs-Jenkins’s Neighbors, as well as Buster Keaton’s signature character and Steve McQueen’s restitution of the former’s legacy within the continuum of Black cultural production. Through this varied archive, Post reveals how deadpan aesthetics function in and between opacity and fugitivity, minimalism and saturation, excess and insensibility.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aAfrican American arts. 0aAfrican Americans in art. 0aAfrican Americans in literature. 0aAmerican literaturexAfrican American authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aFacial expression in art. 0aFacial expression in literature. 7aART / Performance.2bisacsh  aAesthetics.  aAnthropomorphism.  aAwayness.  aBlackness.  aDeadpan.  aEmpiricism.  aExcess.  aFaçade.  aFugitivity.  aIndestructability.  aInexpression.  aInsentience.  aKeaton.  aLooming.  aMcQueen.  aMinimalism.  aMinstrel.  aModernity.  aMonochrome.  aObjecthood.  aObscurity.  aOpacity.  aPortraiture.  aRespectability.  aRiddle.  aSheerness.  aSpecimen.  aStereotype.  aSubjectivity.  aTheatrical.  aThreat.  aTransparency.  aaffect.  agesture.  aperformance.  aresistance.  avisuality.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311075163540uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479811229.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479811229423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479811229/original  a978-3-11-075163-5  New York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_CL_AD  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_AD  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL